• DOMAIN: Automobile¶

• CONTEXT: The data concerns city-cycle fuel consumption in miles per gallon, to be predicted in terms of 3 multivalued discrete and 5 continuous attributes¶

• DATA DESCRIPTION: The data concerns city-cycle fuel consumption in miles per gallon¶

• Attribute Information:¶

1. mpg: continuous

2. cylinders: multi-valued discrete

3. displacement: continuous

4. horsepower: continuous

5. weight: continuous

6. acceleration: continuous

7. model year: multi-valued discrete

8. origin: multi-valued discrete

9. car name: string (unique for each instance)

• PROJECT OBJECTIVE: Goal is to cluster the data and treat them as individual datasets to train Regression models to predict ‘mpg’¶

data=df.drop('mpg',axis=1)
#Threshold for removing correlated variables
threshold = 0.9

# Absolute value correlation matrix
corr_matrix = data.corr().abs()
corr_matrix.head()

# Upper triangle of correlations
upper = corr_matrix.where(np.triu(np.ones(corr_matrix.shape), k=1).astype(np.bool))
upper.head()

# Select columns with correlations above threshold
to_drop = [column for column in upper.columns if any(upper[column] > threshold)]

print('There are %d columns to remove :' % (len(to_drop)))

print(to_drop)

K-Means Clustering¶

In [92]:
cluster_range = range( 2, 6 )   # expect 3 to four clusters from the pair panel visual inspection hence restricting from 2 to 6
cluster_errors = []
for num_clusters in cluster_range:
  clusters = KMeans( num_clusters,random_state=1)
  clusters.fit(df_scaled)
  labels = clusters.labels_
  centroids = clusters.cluster_centers_
  cluster_errors.append( clusters.inertia_ )
clusters_df = pd.DataFrame( { "num_clusters":cluster_range, "cluster_errors": cluster_errors } )

Finding optimal no. of clusters using Elbow Method

In [96]:
#Finding optimal no. of clusters
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
clusters=range(1,10)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k,random_state=1)
    model.fit(df_scaled)
    prediction=model.predict(df_scaled)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(df_scaled, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / df_scaled.shape[0])


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
Out[96]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting k with the Elbow Method')

We can see 3 and 5 are clusters are correct for this data. Both seems to be optimum number of clusters.

Since our EDA suggests there are three distributions of data we will go on with 3 clusters.

Dendogram

In [119]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.title('Agglomerative Hierarchical Clustering Dendogram')
plt.xlabel('sample index')
plt.ylabel('Distance')
dendrogram(Z, leaf_rotation=90.,color_threshold = 40, leaf_font_size=8. )
plt.tight_layout()
  • Dendogram indicates that we can go on with three clusters.
  • Cophenet index is a measure of the correlation between the distance of points in feature space and distance on dendrogram,closer it is to 1, the better is the clustering
  • We will get different dendograms based on distance measure between the cluster so we can choose the best distance method based on cophenet index.

Difference in using K-means and Hierarchical clustering¶

Hierarchical Cluster Dataset.

In [125]:
print('Hierarchical cluster 1: ',df_hier_cluster1.shape)
print('Hierarchical cluster 2: ',df_hier_cluster2.shape)
print('Hierarchical cluster 3: ',df_hier_cluster3.shape)

Hierarchical cluster 1:  (145, 6)
Hierarchical cluster 2:  (151, 6)
Hierarchical cluster 3:  (102, 6)

K-Means Cluster Dataset

In [126]:
print('Kmeans cluster 1: ',df_Kmeans_cluster1.shape)
print('Kmeans cluster 2: ',df_Kmenas_cluster2.shape)
print('Kmeans cluster 3: ',df_Kmeans_cluster3.shape)

Kmeans cluster 1:  (104, 6)
Kmeans cluster 2:  (143, 6)
Kmeans cluster 3:  (151, 6)

In K Means clustering, there is difference in results by algorithms for multiple runs while Hierarchical results are reproducible.

K Means clustering needed advance knowledge of K i.e. no. of clusters one want to divide your data while in hierarchical clustering one can stop at any number of clusters, one find appropriate by interpreting the dendrogram.

The range of mean values belongs to each cluster in kmeans is more while the range is less in hierarchical.

Distribution of data looks similar in each clusters.

Optimal clusters and its reasons¶

  • In Hierarchical clustering we can clearly see that three clusters are optimal for this data. We can clearly see all three clusters are different.
  • As already seen in pairplot three spikes are available for many varaibles, indicating there is three different similarity in data.
  • In Kmeans we have seen in elbow curve that there is bend when k=3. Even when we tried with 5 clusters, Two Clusters had similar behaviour. Two clusters are close to each other.
  • The cophenet index and silhouette score is good when we have 3 clusters.
  • Above are the reasons behind having 3 clusters in the data.

Model with clustering vs Model without Clustering¶

  • We are getting high accuracy when model is built on entire data.
  • But coefficients values are different in single model vs cluster models.
  • From single model we can say origin has no effect for this data but when we built model on sepearte clusters we can see some coefficinet value for particular cluster.
  • From cluster model we can see horsepower has huge negative impact on cluster having high mpg values. This inference is not possible in single model.
  • These are advantages on creating separate clusters. Though the accuracy is less for cluster models interpretation of coefficients are clear in these models

Improvisation¶

  • Quality: Quality of the data seems pretty decent except few missing values, rest were in place. Along with these details if data is provided for how many km it ran we can able to predict better. Some uses cars daily or some will use in daily basis .So by Km ran we can predict mpg accurately
  • Quantity: Even though the quantity of the data was sufficient to build a good model, for each separate cluster data is less to predict. Tt is always beneficial to collect more and more data. So, my only suggestion would be to collect more and more data
  • Variety: We have just dealt with the structured tabular data in our model building process and used a supervised learning method which deals with only structured data. But as far as variety of the data is concerned, it is always helpful to collect more and more data in any form that we could work. Like, it may be helpful if the data collection team could collect some more category of information related to car.
  • Velocity: Since we are not doing any real-time analysis. So it would be difficult to comment on the velocity of the data. But as far as the entire process is concerned, it is always beneficial to collect the data as fast as possible, so that we could come up with better strategies to cluster and predict the data. Data would be of no use if it gets outdated and then it would be difficult to predict car's mpg today based on outdated data.
  • Veracity: Since the data has been provided by the automobile team itself, hence the data is completely authentic. As far as noise and abnormalities in the data are concerned, the abnormalities that we saw in the data is not because of the inauthentic data but due to their own nature.
